div.p:
Guest. Passion or action arising from a certain power, 

            from the concurrence of things with each other. Perhaps, 

            Theætetus, you have not heard their answer to this question; 

            but I have, through my familiarity with them.

Guest. And we will speak of other things in this way ; 

            since the nature of the different appears to be one of entities; 

            and as it exists, it is necessary for us to lay down the parts of 

            it, as no less existing.

Guest. I will then pronounce you a discourse, having 

            united a thing with an action, through a noun and a verb ; 

            and do you tell me of what it is the discourse.

Guest. You know then that it is difficult to bisect these; 

            and the reason will, I think, as we advance, be not the less 

            apparent.

Guest. Let us then separate them like a victim piecemeal; 

            since we cannot do so by a bisection: for it is always requisite 

            to cut into the nearest number possible.

Guest. As far as experiment goes, it will be evident. But 

            let us endeavour to show it by means of music. Tell me, 

            then-

Soc. It binds them then, as it appears, by a certain desire; 

            since it binds them with the greatest bond, and not with 

            necessity.

Soc. Let us then, by the gods, free ourselves from the gods; 

            for I fear to discourse about them. But about some others, 

            if you wish it, propose as questions, that you may see of what 

            kind are the horses of Euthyphro.94

Soc. Now the medicinal business produces medical results; 

            and the carpenter's business carpentry results: or how say 

            you ?
